Bail defenders also point to the taxes paid by the bail industry – and cite studies showing cost savings to counties.
It’s a problem not just for the poor people who are affected, but also for the state’s perpetually overcrowded jail system.
The U.S. Justice Department also has weighed in on behalf of bail reform in a Georgia case.
As the San Francisco Chronicle reported, “Nunley refused, at least for now, to dismiss a claim that the bail system is unfairly punitive.” Nunley is an appointee of President Barack Obama.
Various compromises could emerge, including measures that eliminate bail for certain cases, or efforts to create easier ways for poor defendants to afford bonds.